    "120558749": {
      "title": "Exponential L 1 output tracking control for positive switched linear systems with time-varying delays",
      "abstract": "Abstract The problem of exponential L 1 output tracking control for positive switched linear systems with time-varying delays is addressed in this paper. The exponential L 1 -gain performance index is introduced to study such a problem. By resorting to the average dwell time approach, and also by constructing an appropriate piecewise co-positive type Lyapunov\u2013Krasovskii functional, a new delay-dependent exponential stability criterion is developed, and the exponential L 1 -gain performance is analyzed. Based on the results obtained, a state feedback controller is constructed such that the exponential L 1 output tracking performance is satisfied. A numerical example is given to demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed method."
    },
    "120583178": {
      "title": "Finite-time 1 control for positive switched linear systems with time-varying delay",
      "abstract": "This paper is concerned with the problem of finite-time L1 control for a class of positive switched linear systems with time-varying delay. Firstly, by using the average dwell time approach, sufficient conditions which can guarantee the L1 finite-time boundedness of the underlying system are given. Then, in virtue of the results obtained, a state feedback controller is designed to ensure that the resulting closed-loop system is finite-time bounded with L1-gain performance. All the obtained results are formulated in terms of linear matrix inequalities (LMIs), which can be solved conveniently. Finally, an example is given to illustrate the efficiency of the proposed method."
    },
    "121920949": {
      "title": "Output feedback L 1 finite-time control of switched positive delayed systems with MDADT",
      "abstract": "Abstract In this paper, the problem of static output-feedback L 1 finite-time control for switched positive systems with time-varying delay is investigated. Mode-dependent average dwell time (MDADT) approach, which permits each subsystem to have its own average dwell time, is adopted in this paper to reduce the conservativeness of the average dwell time method. By constructing multiple linear copositive Lyapunov functions (MLCLFs), static output-feedback controllers are designed and a sufficient condition is derived to ensure that the closed-loop system is positive and L 1 finite-time bounded. Finally, a simulation example is given to illustrate the effectiveness and potential of the proposed method."
    }
  }
}